Here's how to implement email/password signup and login with the Appwrite Web SDK:

## 1. Install the SDK

```bash
npm install appwrite
```

## 2. Set Up the Client & Implement Auth

```typescript
import { Client, Account, ID } from 'appwrite';

// Initialize the client
const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')  // Replace with your endpoint
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');                            // Replace with your project ID

const account = new Account(client);

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ SIGNUP ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
async function signUp(email: string, password: string, name?: string) {
    try {
        const user = await account.create({
            userId: ID.unique(),
            email,
            password,
            name, // optional
        });
        console.log('Account created:', user);
        return user;
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Signup failed:', error);
        throw error;
    }
}

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ LOGIN ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
async function logIn(email: string, password: string) {
    try {
        const session = await account.createEmailPasswordSession({
            email,
            password,
        });
        console.log('Session created:', session);
        return session;
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Login failed:', error);
        throw error;
    }
}

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ USAGE ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// Sign up
await signUp('user@example.com', 'securePassword123', 'John Doe');

// Log in
await logIn('user@example.com', 'securePassword123');

// Get the currently logged-in user
const user = await account.get();
console.log('Current user:', user);

// Log out
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' });
```

## Key Points

- **`ID.unique()`** generates a unique user ID automatically.
- **`account.create()`** registers a new user account.
- **`account.createEmailPasswordSession()`** creates a session (logs the user in).
- **`account.get()`** retrieves the currently authenticated user.
- **`account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' })`** logs the user out.

## Error Handling

Wrap calls in try/catch and handle `AppwriteException`:

```typescript
import { AppwriteException } from 'appwrite';

try {
    await account.createEmailPasswordSession({ email, password });
} catch (err) {
    if (err instanceof AppwriteException) {
        console.error(err.message);  // e.g. "Invalid credentials"
        console.error(err.code);     // e.g. 401
        console.error(err.type);     // e.g. "user_invalid_credentials"
    }
}
```

That's all you need for basic email/password authentication with the Appwrite Web SDK!

# How Appwrite Sessions Work

Appwrite uses **server-side sessions** to authenticate users. When a user logs in, Appwrite creates a session on the server and returns a **session secret** ŌĆö a token that the client must send with subsequent requests to prove their identity.

---

## 1. How Sessions Are Created

Sessions are created through the **Account** service. There are several authentication methods, each producing a session:

### Email/Password Login

```typescript
const account = new Account(client);
const session = await account.createEmailPasswordSession({
    email: 'user@example.com',
    password: 'password123'
});
// session.secret  ŌĆö the session token
// session.userId  ŌĆö the authenticated user's ID
// session.expire  ŌĆö ISO 8601 expiration timestamp
```

### OAuth2 Login (Web)

```typescript
account.createOAuth2Session({
    provider: OAuthProvider.Github,
    success: 'https://example.com/success',
    failure: 'https://example.com/fail',
    scopes: ['repo', 'user']  // optional provider-specific scopes
});
```

The browser is redirected to the OAuth provider, then back to your success URL with the session automatically established via a cookie.

### OAuth2 Login (React Native / Custom Flow)

Since `createOAuth2Session()` doesn't work on React Native, you use a two-step token exchange:

```typescript
// Step 1: Get an OAuth login URL
const loginUrl = await account.createOAuth2Token({
    provider: OAuthProvider.Github,
    success: 'myapp://callback',
    failure: 'myapp://callback',
});

// Step 2: After redirect, exchange the token for a session
await account.createSession({
    userId: url.searchParams.get('userId'),
    secret: url.searchParams.get('secret'),
});
```

### Server-Side Rendering (SSR) Login

SSR apps use the **admin client** (with an API key) to create sessions, then set the session secret as an HTTP-only cookie:

```typescript
const account = new Account(adminClient);
const session = await account.createEmailPasswordSession({
    email: req.body.email,
    password: req.body.password,
});

res.cookie('a_session_[PROJECT_ID]', session.secret, {
    httpOnly: true,
    secure: true,
    sameSite: 'strict',
    expires: new Date(session.expire),
    path: '/',
});
```

---

## 2. How Sessions Are Managed

### Client-Side (Browser / React Native)

The SDK automatically stores the session secret and sends it with every request. You don't need to manually handle tokens on the client.

### Server-Side (SSR)

You must create a **per-request session client** that uses the session cookie:

```typescript
// Extract the session cookie
const sessionCookie = req.cookies['a_session_[PROJECT_ID]'];

// Create a fresh client for this request
const sessionClient = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]')
    .setSession(sessionCookie);

// Optionally forward the user-agent for audit logs
sessionClient.setForwardedUserAgent(req.headers['user-agent']);

// Now act on behalf of the user
const account = new Account(sessionClient);
const user = await account.get();
```

> **Important:** Never share session clients between requests. Create a new one per request.

### Session Properties

Each session object (`Models.Session`) contains:
- **`$id`** ŌĆö unique session ID
- **`userId`** ŌĆö the authenticated user
- **`secret`** ŌĆö the session token (used in cookies/headers)
- **`expire`** ŌĆö ISO 8601 expiration date
- **`provider`** ŌĆö auth method used (e.g., `email`, `github`, `google`)
- **`ip`** ŌĆö IP address at creation
- **`userAgent`** ŌĆö user agent string at creation
- **`current`** ŌĆö boolean indicating if this is the current session

### Session Cookie

The cookie name is always `a_session_<PROJECT_ID>`. It must be:
- `httpOnly` ŌĆö not accessible via JavaScript (prevents XSS)
- `secure` ŌĆö only sent over HTTPS
- `sameSite: 'strict'` ŌĆö prevents CSRF

---

## 3. How Sessions Are Deleted

### Logout (Client-Side)

```typescript
// Delete the current session
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' });

// Delete a specific session by ID
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: '[SESSION_ID]' });
```

### Logout (Server-Side)

```typescript
const account = new Account(adminClient);
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' });

// Also clear the cookie
res.clearCookie('a_session_[PROJECT_ID]');
```

### Delete All Sessions

You can delete all sessions for a user (logging them out everywhere):

```typescript
// Using the Account service (client-side, requires current session)
await account.deleteSessions();

// Using the Users service (server-side, requires API key)
const users = new Users(adminClient);
await users.deleteSessions({ userId: '[USER_ID]' });
```

---

## 4. Session Limits

Appwrite enforces a **maximum number of active sessions per user**. This is configured at the project level under **Auth > Security > Sessions Limit**.

### Default & Configuration

- **Default limit:** 10 sessions per user
- **Configurable range:** 1ŌĆō100 sessions
- **Set via CLI** in `appwrite.config.json`:

```json
{
    "settings": {
        "auth": {
            "security": {
                "sessionsLimit": 10
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Or via the Appwrite Console under **Auth > Settings > Security**.

### What Happens at the Limit

When a user reaches the session limit and tries to create a new session, the **oldest session** is automatically deleted to make room. This ensures the user can always log in without manual session cleanup.

### Best Practices

- **Keep the default (10)** for most applications ŌĆö it allows users to be logged in across multiple devices/browsers.
- **Lower the limit** for high-security apps (e.g., banking) to reduce the attack surface.
- **Raise the limit** if your users commonly use many devices, but be aware of the security trade-off.
- **Use `deleteSessions()`** on password changes or security-sensitive events to force re-authentication on all devices.

---

## Summary

| Aspect | Details |
|--------|---------|
| **Creation** | `createEmailPasswordSession()`, `createOAuth2Session()`, `createSession()` (token exchange) |
| **Storage** | Client SDK auto-manages; SSR uses `a_session_<PROJECT_ID>` HTTP-only cookie |
| **Authentication** | Session secret sent via `X-Appwrite-Session` header or cookie |
| **Deletion** | `deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' })` or `deleteSessions()` for all |
| **Limit** | Configurable 1ŌĆō100 (default 10); oldest session auto-removed when limit reached |
| **Expiration** | Configurable per project; sessions have an `expire` timestamp |

Great question! Let me explain the difference between these two Account methods.

## `account.deleteSession(sessionId)`

**Deletes a single, specific session** by its ID.

```typescript
// Delete the current session (log out from this device)
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' });

// Delete a specific session by its ID (e.g., log out a different device)
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: '[SESSION_ID]' });
```

- You can pass `'current'` as the session ID to target the session making the request.
- Or pass a specific session ID string to target another session (e.g., one from a different device/browser).

## `account.deleteSessions()`

**Deletes all sessions** for the authenticated user at once.

```typescript
// Log out from ALL devices
await account.deleteSessions();
```

- No parameters needed.
- This is a bulk operation ŌĆö it removes every active session the user has across all devices and browsers.

---

## When to Use Each

| Scenario | Use |
|----------|-----|
| **Log out from the current device/browser** (e.g., a "Sign Out" button) | `deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' })` |
| **Log out a specific other device** (e.g., "log out that old phone") | `deleteSession({ sessionId: '[SESSION_ID]' })` |
| **"Log out everywhere" / "Sign out of all devices"** security feature | `deleteSessions()` |
| **Password change flow** ŌĆö invalidate all existing sessions so the user must re-login | `deleteSessions()` |
| **Account compromise / suspicious activity** ŌĆö force logout from all devices | `deleteSessions()` |

### Key Differences

| Aspect | `deleteSession` | `deleteSessions` |
|--------|----------------|------------------|
| **Scope** | One session | All sessions |
| **Parameter** | `sessionId` (string or `'current'`) | None |
| **Use case** | Targeted logout | Bulk logout / security reset |
| **Typical UI** | "Sign Out" button | "Sign Out of All Devices" button |

### Example: Building a Security Settings Page

```typescript
// User clicks "Sign Out" on their current device
await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' });

// User clicks "Sign Out of All Other Devices" (keep current)
const sessions = await account.listSessions();
for (const session of sessions.sessions) {
    if (session.$id !== currentSessionId) {
        await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: session.$id });
    }
}

// User clicks "Sign Out Everywhere" (including current)
await account.deleteSessions();
```

**Bottom line:** Use `deleteSession` for granular, single-session control (like a standard logout), and `deleteSessions` when you need to revoke all sessions at once (security resets, password changes, or "log out everywhere" features).

Here's the complete code using the Appwrite Web SDK's `TablesDB` API to create a database, a `tasks` table with typed columns, and insert a row.

> **Important:** Creating databases and tables requires **server-side** access (an API key). Row insertion can be done from the client if the table's permissions allow it. The code below shows both parts ŌĆö use the server-side block in a Node.js backend or Appwrite Function, and the client-side block in your web app.

```typescript
// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// 1. Imports (Web SDK)
// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
import { Client, TablesDB, ID } from 'appwrite';

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// 2. Client setup
// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')  // e.g. 'https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1'
    .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// 3. Create database (server-side only)
// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// Requires an API key with `databases.write` scope.
// Run this in a Node.js backend or Appwrite Function.
const database = await tablesDB.create({
    databaseId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'My App Database'
});
console.log(`Database created: ${database.$id}`);

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// 4. Create "tasks" table with columns (server-side only)
// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
const table = await tablesDB.createTable({
    databaseId: database.$id,
    tableId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'tasks',
    columns: [
        { key: 'title',    type: 'varchar',  size: 255,   required: true  },
        { key: 'completed', type: 'boolean',                required: true  },
        { key: 'dueDate',  type: 'datetime',                required: false },
    ]
});
console.log(`Table created: ${table.$id}`);

// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// 5. Insert a row (client or server)
// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ
// On the client, the table must have appropriate
// permissions (e.g., `Permission.create(Role.any())`
// or `Role.user(...)`) for the current user to write.
const row = await tablesDB.createRow({
    databaseId: database.$id,
    tableId: table.$id,
    rowId: ID.unique(),
    data: {
        title: 'Buy groceries',
        completed: false,
        dueDate: '2025-12-31T23:59:59.000Z'  // ISO 8601 format
    }
});
console.log(`Row inserted: ${row.$id}`);
```

---

## Key points

| Step | Where to run | Required auth |
|------|-------------|---------------|
| **Create database** | Server-side (Node.js / Appwrite Function) | API key with `databases.write` scope |
| **Create table** | Server-side | API key with `databases.write` scope |
| **Insert row** | Client or server | Depends on table permissions |

### Column types used

| Column | Type | Notes |
|--------|------|-------|
| `title` | `varchar` (size 255) | Inline, fully indexable, max 16,383 chars |
| `completed` | `boolean` | `true` or `false` |
| `dueDate` | `datetime` | ISO 8601 string (e.g. `"2025-12-31T23:59:59.000Z"`) |

### Server-side setup (if you need a complete backend script)

```typescript
// server-side.mjs
import { Client, TablesDB, ID } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject(process.env.APPWRITE_PROJECT_ID)
    .setKey(process.env.APPWRITE_API_KEY);   // <-- API key required

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

async function setup() {
    // ... same code as above ...
}
setup().catch(console.error);
```

### Client-side row insertion with permissions

When inserting from the client, make sure the table (or the row itself) grants the current user `create` access. For example, if you want any authenticated user to create tasks:

```typescript
// Set during table creation (server-side)
await tablesDB.createTable({
    databaseId: database.$id,
    tableId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'tasks',
    columns: [ /* ... */ ],
    permissions: [
        Permission.create(Role.any()),   // any authenticated user can create rows
        Permission.read(Role.any()),
        Permission.update(Role.any()),
        Permission.delete(Role.any()),
    ]
});
```

Or set per-row permissions at insert time:

```typescript
import { Permission, Role } from 'appwrite';

const row = await tablesDB.createRow({
    databaseId: database.$id,
    tableId: table.$id,
    rowId: ID.unique(),
    data: { title: 'Buy groceries', completed: false, dueDate: '2025-12-31T23:59:59.000Z' },
    permissions: [
        Permission.read(Role.user('<USER_ID>')),
        Permission.update(Role.user('<USER_ID>')),
        Permission.delete(Role.user('<USER_ID>')),
    ]
});
```

> **Tip:** Use `ID.unique()` to auto-generate IDs for databases, tables, and rows. The `dueDate` value must be an ISO 8601 string ŌĆö JavaScript's `new Date().toISOString()` works perfectly.

The Appwrite TypeScript SDK provides a `Query` class with a rich set of methods for filtering, sorting, and paginating rows in **TablesDB**. Here's a complete guide.

---

## Basic Setup

```typescript
import { Client, TablesDB, Query } from 'appwrite';        // Web / React Native
// or
import { Client, TablesDB, Query } from 'node-appwrite';   // Node.js / Deno

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]')
    .setKey('[API_KEY]');  // server-side only

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);
```

