You canŌĆÖt safely create databases/tables from a public browser app with the Web SDK because schema creation is an admin/server-side operation. Use `TablesDB` with the current API from a trusted environment, such as an Appwrite Function or backend using `node-appwrite`.

```ts
import { Client, TablesDB, ID, Permission, Role } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>')
  .setKey('<APPWRITE_API_KEY>');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

async function setupTasksTable() {
  // 1. Create database
  const database = await tablesDB.create({
    databaseId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'Tasks Database',
  });

  // 2. Create "tasks" table with columns
  const table = await tablesDB.createTable({
    databaseId: database.$id,
    tableId: 'tasks',
    name: 'Tasks',
    columns: [
      {
        key: 'title',
        type: 'varchar',
        size: 255,
        required: true,
      },
      {
        key: 'completed',
        type: 'boolean',
        required: true,
      },
      {
        key: 'dueDate',
        type: 'datetime',
        required: false,
      },
    ],
    permissions: [
      Permission.read(Role.any()),
      Permission.create(Role.users()),
    ],
  });

  // 3. Insert a row
  const task = await tablesDB.createRow({
    databaseId: database.$id,
    tableId: table.$id,
    rowId: ID.unique(),
    data: {
      title: 'Finish Appwrite setup',
      completed: false,
      dueDate: new Date('2026-01-15T12:00:00.000Z').toISOString(),
    },
    permissions: [
      Permission.read(Role.any()),
      Permission.update(Role.users()),
      Permission.delete(Role.users()),
    ],
  });

  console.log({ database, table, task });
}

setupTasksTable().catch(console.error);
```

For a browser app using the Web SDK, create the database/table ahead of time on the server, then only insert rows from the client:

```ts
import { Client, TablesDB, ID } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

await tablesDB.createRow({
  databaseId: '<DATABASE_ID>',
  tableId: 'tasks',
  rowId: ID.unique(),
  data: {
    title: 'Finish Appwrite setup',
    completed: false,
    dueDate: new Date('2026-01-15T12:00:00.000Z').toISOString(),
  },
});

Use `TablesDB.listRows()` and pass an array of `Query` helpers in the `queries` option. Each `Query.*()` call creates one query condition.

```ts
import { Client, TablesDB, Query } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

const result = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.equal('status', 'active'),
    Query.limit(10),
  ],
});

console.log(result.total);
console.log(result.rows); // In some older SDK/model typings this may be `documents`
```

## Filtering rows

Queries are combined with `AND` by default.

```ts
const activeTodos = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.equal('status', 'active'),
    Query.equal('done', false),
  ],
});
```

More filter examples:

```ts
queries: [
  Query.equal('category', 'work'),              // category == "work"
  Query.notEqual('status', 'archived'),         // status != "archived"
  Query.greaterThan('priority', 2),             // priority > 2
  Query.lessThanEqual('price', 100),            // price <= 100
  Query.between('age', 18, 65),                 // 18 <= age <= 65
  Query.isNull('deletedAt'),                    // deletedAt is null
  Query.isNotNull('publishedAt'),               // publishedAt is not null
  Query.startsWith('title', 'Appwrite'),        // title starts with "Appwrite"
  Query.contains('tags', 'backend'),            // array/string contains value
]
```

You can pass an array to `Query.equal()` for an `IN`-style query:

```ts
const posts = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.equal('status', ['draft', 'published']),
  ],
});
```

Full-text search:

```ts
const searchResults = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.search('content', 'serverless functions'),
  ],
});
```

`Query.search()` requires a full-text index on the column.

## Sorting rows

Use `Query.orderAsc()` or `Query.orderDesc()`.

```ts
const newestPosts = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.equal('status', 'published'),
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
  ],
});
```

Sort by a custom column:

```ts
const topProducts = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.orderDesc('rating'),
    Query.orderAsc('name'),
  ],
});
```

## Limiting results

Use `Query.limit()` to control how many rows are returned.

```ts
const firstTen = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.limit(10),
  ],
});
```

Default limit is usually `25`; maximum is `100`.

## Offset pagination

Offset pagination skips a number of rows.

```ts
const page = 3;
const limit = 20;

const result = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
    Query.limit(limit),
    Query.offset((page - 1) * limit),
  ],
});
```

This is simple, but for large datasets cursor pagination is preferred.

## Cursor pagination

Cursor pagination uses the last or first row ID from the previous page.

```ts
const firstPage = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
    Query.limit(20),
  ],
});

const lastRow = firstPage.rows[firstPage.rows.length - 1];

const secondPage = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
    Query.limit(20),
    Query.cursorAfter(lastRow.$id),
  ],
});
```

To go backward:

```ts
const previousPage = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
    Query.limit(20),
    Query.cursorBefore(firstRow.$id),
  ],
});
```

## Combining conditions with OR

By default, query conditions are `AND`ed together. Use `Query.or()` when needed.

```ts
const urgentOrHighPriority = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
  tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
  queries: [
    Query.or([
      Query.equal('urgent', true),
      Query.greaterThanEqual('priority', 8),
    ]),
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
    Query.limit(25),
  ],
});
```

## Complete example

```ts
const result = await tablesDB.listRows({
  databaseId: 'main',
  tableId: 'tasks',
  queries: [
    Query.equal('status', 'open'),
    Query.greaterThanEqual('priority', 3),
    Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'),
    Query.limit(20),
  ],
});

for (const row of result.rows) {
  console.log(row.$id, row.title, row.priority);
}
```

In short: pass `Query` helpers to `listRows()`. Use filters to narrow results, `orderAsc`/`orderDesc` to sort, `limit` to cap results, and `offset` or cursor queries for pagination.

```js
// src/main.js

export default async ({ req, res, log, error }) => {
  const body = req.bodyJson;

  if (!body || typeof body.name !== 'string' || body.name.trim() === '') {
    return res.json(
      {
        error: 'Missing or invalid "name" field',
      },
      400
    );
  }

  const name = body.name.trim();

  return res.json({
    greeting: `Hello, ${name}!`,
  });
};
```

Example JSON request body:

```json
{
  "name": "Alex"
}
```

Example response:

```json
{
  "greeting": "Hello, Alex!"
}
```

You can upload files and get preview URLs with the Appwrite **Web SDK**, but creating a bucket is an **admin/server-side operation**. Do **not** create buckets from browser code or expose an API key in the frontend.

Below is a safe setup:

---

## 1. Server-side bucket creation

Use `node-appwrite` in a backend script, server route, or Appwrite Function.

```ts
// create-bucket.ts
import { Client, Storage, ID, Permission, Role } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>')
  .setKey(process.env.APPWRITE_API_KEY!);

const storage = new Storage(client);

const bucket = await storage.createBucket({
  bucketId: 'images',
  name: 'Images',
  permissions: [
    // Anyone can read files from this bucket
    Permission.read(Role.any()),

    // Only authenticated users can upload files
    Permission.create(Role.users()),
  ],
  fileSecurity: true,
  enabled: true,
  maximumFileSize: 10 * 1024 * 1024, // 10 MB
  allowedFileExtensions: ['jpg', 'jpeg', 'png', 'webp', 'gif'],
  compression: 'gzip',
  encryption: true,
  antivirus: true,
});

console.log('Bucket created:', bucket);
```

Your API key needs the appropriate Storage/Buckets scope.

---

## 2. Browser upload and preview URL with Appwrite Web SDK

```ts
// appwrite-storage.ts
import { Client, Storage, ID, Permission, Role } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>');

const storage = new Storage(client);

const BUCKET_ID = 'images';

export async function uploadImageAndGetPreview(file: File) {
  if (!file.type.startsWith('image/')) {
    throw new Error('Only image files are allowed.');
  }

  const uploadedFile = await storage.createFile({
    bucketId: BUCKET_ID,
    fileId: ID.unique(),
    file,
    permissions: [
      // Publicly readable, required if the preview should be visible without login
      Permission.read(Role.any()),

      // The signed-in user who uploads can update/delete their own file
      Permission.update(Role.users()),
      Permission.delete(Role.users()),
    ],
  });

  const previewUrl = storage.getFilePreview({
    bucketId: BUCKET_ID,
    fileId: uploadedFile.$id,
    width: 600,
    height: 600,
    quality: 90,
  });

  return {
    file: uploadedFile,
    previewUrl,
  };
}
```

---

## 3. Example usage with an `<input type="file">`

```ts
import { uploadImageAndGetPreview } from './appwrite-storage';

const input = document.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>('#image-input')!;
const img = document.querySelector<HTMLImageElement>('#preview')!;

input.addEventListener('change', async () => {
  const file = input.files?.[0];
  if (!file) return;

  try {
    const { file: uploadedFile, previewUrl } = await uploadImageAndGetPreview(file);

    console.log('Uploaded file:', uploadedFile);
    console.log('Preview URL:', previewUrl);

    img.src = previewUrl.toString();
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Upload failed:', error);
  }
});
```

```html
<input id="image-input" type="file" accept="image/*" />
<img id="preview" alt="Image preview" />
```

---

If files should only be visible to logged-in users, replace:

```ts
Permission.read(Role.any())
```

with:

```ts
Permission.read(Role.users())
```

To set up push notifications with **Appwrite Messaging**, the flow is:

1. **Create a push provider**
   - In the Appwrite Console, go to **Messaging ŌåÆ Providers ŌåÆ Create provider**.
   - For push notifications, Appwrite supports:
     - **Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM)** ŌĆö commonly used for Android, web, and Firebase-based iOS apps.
     - **Apple Push Notification service (APNs)** ŌĆö native Apple push notifications for iOS/macOS.
   - Configure the provider with the required credentials from Firebase or Apple.

2. **Register a user device as a push target**
   - Your app must first get the device push token from FCM or APNs.
   - Then register that token with Appwrite, usually from the authenticated client:

```ts
import { Client, Account, ID } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>');

const account = new Account(client);

// deviceToken comes from FCM or APNs
await account.createPushTarget({
  targetId: ID.unique(),
  identifier: deviceToken,
  providerId: '<PROVIDER_ID>',
});
```

3. **Create a topic and subscribe targets**
   - Topics are groups of subscribers.
   - Use a trusted backend or Appwrite Function with an API key.

```ts
import { Client, Messaging, ID } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject(process.env.APPWRITE_PROJECT_ID)
  .setKey(process.env.APPWRITE_API_KEY);

const messaging = new Messaging(client);

// Create topic
await messaging.createTopic({
  topicId: 'news',
  name: 'News Updates',
});

// Subscribe a registered push target to the topic
await messaging.createSubscriber({
  topicId: 'news',
  subscriberId: ID.unique(),
  targetId: '<TARGET_ID>',
});
```

4. **Send a push notification to the topic**

```ts
await messaging.createPush({
  messageId: ID.unique(),
  title: 'Breaking News',
  body: 'A new article is available.',
  topics: ['news'],
  data: {
    articleId: '123',
  },
});
```

The `topics` array contains topic IDs, not topic names. Appwrite will send the push notification to all push targets subscribed to that topic.

Appwrite Messaging targets **delivery targets**, not just raw addresses. A **target** is a concrete destination for a user, such as an email address, phone number, or push token. Messages can be addressed in three ways:

1. **Users** ŌĆö send to one or more Appwrite user IDs. Appwrite resolves the user to their compatible targets.
2. **Topics** ŌĆö send to all targets subscribed to a Messaging topic.
3. **Targets** ŌĆö send directly to specific target IDs, useful for one device, one phone number, or one email target.

You can use any combination of `users`, `topics`, and `targets` when creating an email, SMS, or push message. Appwrite expands topics and users into targets for the relevant message type.

Example using the Node SDK:

```ts
import { Client, Messaging, ID } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>')
  .setKey('<API_KEY>');

const messaging = new Messaging(client);
```

### Send to specific users

```ts
await messaging.createEmail({
  messageId: ID.unique(),
  subject: 'Welcome!',
  content: 'Thanks for joining.',
  users: ['userId1', 'userId2'],
});
```

For push:

```ts
await messaging.createPush({
  messageId: ID.unique(),
  title: 'New update',
  body: 'Check out what changed.',
  users: ['userId1'],
});
```

### Send to a topic

First, targets must be subscribed to the topic:

```ts
await messaging.createSubscriber({
  topicId: 'announcements',
  subscriberId: ID.unique(),
  targetId: 'targetId1',
});
```

Then send to the topic:

```ts
await messaging.createPush({
  messageId: ID.unique(),
  title: 'Announcement',
  body: 'We launched a new feature.',
  topics: ['announcements'],
});
```

### Send to individual targets

Use this when you want to address a specific destination, such as one push device token or one phone/email target:

```ts
await messaging.createSms({
  messageId: ID.unique(),
  content: 'Your verification code is 123456',
  targets: ['targetId1'],
});
```

In short: **users are resolved to their targets, topics are groups of subscribed targets, and targets are the final delivery endpoints.**

```ts
import { Client, Realtime, Channel, Models } from 'appwrite';

const PROJECT_ID = '[PROJECT_ID]';
const DATABASE_ID = '[DATABASE_ID]';
const TABLE_ID = '[TABLE_ID]';
const BUCKET_ID = '[BUCKET_ID]';

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
  .setProject(PROJECT_ID);

const realtime = new Realtime(client);

async function subscribeToRowsAndUploads() {
  const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(
    [
      // All row create/update/delete events in this table
      Channel.tablesdb(DATABASE_ID).table(TABLE_ID).row(),

      // All file create/update/delete events in this bucket
      Channel.bucket(BUCKET_ID).file(),
    ],
    (response) => {
      const { events, payload } = response;

      const isTableRowEvent = events.some((event) =>
        event.includes(`tablesdb.${DATABASE_ID}.tables.${TABLE_ID}.rows`)
      );

      const isFileEvent = events.some((event) =>
        event.includes(`buckets.${BUCKET_ID}.files`)
      );

      if (isTableRowEvent) {
        const row = payload as Models.Document;

        if (events.some((event) => event.endsWith('.create'))) {
          console.log('Row created:', row);
          handleRowCreated(row);
        } else if (events.some((event) => event.endsWith('.update'))) {
          console.log('Row updated:', row);
          handleRowUpdated(row);
        } else if (events.some((event) => event.endsWith('.delete'))) {
          console.log('Row deleted:', row);
          handleRowDeleted(row);
        }

        return;
      }

      if (isFileEvent) {
        const file = payload as Models.File;

        if (events.some((event) => event.endsWith('.create'))) {
          console.log('File uploaded:', file);
          handleFileUploaded(file);
        } else if (events.some((event) => event.endsWith('.update'))) {
          console.log('File updated:', file);
          handleFileUpdated(file);
        } else if (events.some((event) => event.endsWith('.delete'))) {
          console.log('File deleted:', file);
          handleFileDeleted(file);
        }
      }
    }
  );

  // Call this when leaving the page/component
  return async () => {
    await subscription.close();
  };
}

function handleRowCreated(row: Models.Document) {
  // Update table UI, add row to state, show notification, etc.
}

function handleRowUpdated(row: Models.Document) {
  // Replace row in state, refresh details panel, etc.
}

function handleRowDeleted(row: Models.Document) {
  // Remove row from state using row.$id
}

function handleFileUploaded(file: Models.File) {
  // Show uploaded file, generate preview URL, update gallery, etc.
}

function handleFileUpdated(file: Models.File) {
  // Refresh file metadata
}

function handleFileDeleted(file: Models.File) {
  // Remove file from UI using file.$id
}

// Start listening
const unsubscribe = await subscribeToRowsAndUploads();

// Later, when done:
// await unsubscribe();
```

This uses one realtime subscription with multiple channels: one for table row changes and one for bucket file events. The callback inspects the event/channel type and dispatches each event to the correct handler.

```ts
const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(
  [
    'tablesdb.[DATABASE_ID].tables.[TABLE_ID].rows',
    'buckets.[BUCKET_ID].files',
  ],
  (response) => {
    console.log(response.events);
    console.log(response.payload);
  }
);
```

